Multi-Image 3D Reconstruction feature.
This process is scientifically known as Photogrammetry or Structure from Motion (SfM). If you were to add this to a technical proposal or a project roadmap, here is how you should explain the logic, workflow, and technical requirements.
Feature: Multi-View 3D Spatial Reconstruction
Concept: This feature allows users to capture a series of overlapping 2D images of an object or environment from different angles. The system then analyzes these images to triangulate depth and geometry, generating a high-fidelity 3D model (mesh) with accurate spatial coordinates.
1. The Technical Workflow (How it Works)
To transform flat images into a 3D structure, the system follows a four-stage pipeline:
 * Feature Detection & Matching: The algorithm identifies unique "keypoints" (edges, corners, or textures) in every image. It then searches for these same keypoints across multiple photos to establish a visual link between them.
 * Structure from Motion (SfM): By calculating the slight shift in the position of these keypoints between photos, the system estimates the exact position and angle of the camera for every shot.
 * Dense Point Cloud Generation: Once the camera positions are known, the system populates the "empty space" by calculating millions of data points, creating a "point cloud" that represents the surface of the object.
 * Meshing & Texturing: The point cloud is converted into a solid 3D mesh (a skin of triangles). Finally, the original colors from the photos are "wrapped" onto this mesh to create a photorealistic 3D model.
2. Key Technical Components
 *Overlap Requirement:To ensure accuracy, images typically need a 60–80% overlap. This allows the software to find enough common points to triangulate depth.
 *Depth Estimation:Uses Epipolar Geometry to determine the 3D coordinates of a point based on its 2D position in two or more images.
 *Processing Engine:Can be handled locally (using frameworks like OpenCV or AliceVision) or via cloud-based API processing for mobile devices with lower compute power
3. User Experience & Interaction
To make this feature intuitive, the UI should provide real-time feedback:
 * Guided Capture: An AR overlay (like a dome or semi-sphere) that shows the user which angles they have already captured and which ones are "missing" to ensure a complete scan.
 * Automatic Quality Check: The system should instantly flag blurry or low-light images that might break the 3D reconstruction before the user finishes the session.
4. Integration Value
In the context of your project, this feature moves the app from "static documentation" to "spatial intelligence." It allows for:
 * Accurate Measurements: Users can measure distances within the 3D space directly from their phone.
 * Exportability: The resulting structure can be exported as .OBJ, .PLY, or .USDZ files for use in CAD, 3D printing, or AR environments.
